p + o = 1438 and p/0.67 = o/0.45<br><br>0.67/p = 0.45/o<br>o = 0.675p<br>=&gt; 1.67p = 1438<br>p = 861<br>=&gt; o = 1438 - 861 = 577<br><br>The primal is in mainhand so calculated probability of an avatar proc is 35/(861*1.6) = 2.5%<br>Calculated duration of test = 861 / 0.67 = 21m 25s<br>Actual duration of test = 21m 43s<br><br>The calculated value is within 20 seconds (1.5%) of the actual value.  It is impossible to calculate the real value exactly because it depends on random factors (offhand and double attacks) but that is pretty damn close.<br><br>Test 10: RB/Primal<br><br>Primary Frequency = 0.56<br>Secondary Frequency = 0.54<br><br>Solve:<br><br>p + o = 1163 and p/0.56 = o/0.54<br><br>p/0.56 = o/0.54<br>o = 0.972p<br>=&gt; 1.972p = 1163<br>p = 590<br>=&gt; o = 1163 - 590 = 573<br><br>The primal is in mainhand so calculated probability of an avatar proc is 14/(573*1.6) = 1.5%<br>Calculated duration of test = 590 / 0.56 = 17m 33s<br>Actual duration of test = 17m 38s<br><br>Again the actual duration is very close (almost exactly the same this time) to the calculated value.  Both of these results seem to validate the model I've chosen (particularly with rounding of delays on hasted weapons).<br><br>The chance of an avatar proc is being difficult to pin down.  I've had figures from 1.5-5.5% and one of those 5.5% values included the only sample with no avatar proc (and thus much lower desterity).  To me it really seems like dexterity has a negligible effect on avatar proc.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showPrevMessage?topicID=11552.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousethebackroomsecretsspoilers.showNextMessage?topicID=11552.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthe